---
import Layout from '../layouts/Layout.astro';
---

<Layout title="Onboard Computer | Mellotech">
  <main class="obc-page">
    <div class="obc-content glass-panel">
      <div class="obc-glow-bar"></div>

      <span class="obc-section-tag font-mono">AVIONICS DEEP DIVE</span>
      <h1 class="obc-page-title">The Onboard Computer</h1>

      <section class="obc-section">
        <h2 class="obc-heading">Overview</h2>
        <p class="obc-text">
          Our OBC is built around the <strong>STM32H743</strong> — a 480 MHz ARM Cortex-M7
          microcontroller with hardware floating point and enough peripheral bandwidth to run
          sensor fusion, actuator control, telemetry, and high-rate data logging concurrently,
          in real time, on a single board. Everything downstream of "the rocket needs to fly
          itself" runs through this chip.
        </p>
        <p class="obc-text">
          The board is organized into independent, purpose-built sections — not because it
          looks impressive on a schematic, but because isolating them is what makes the whole
          system trustworthy in flight.
        </p>
      </section>

      <section class="obc-section">
        <h2 class="obc-heading">Power</h2>
        <p class="obc-text">
          Flight electronics fail more often from bad power than bad code. Our power section
          starts with reverse-polarity protection built around a P-channel MOSFET rather than
          a simple diode — it costs a few more components, but drops essentially zero voltage
          under load, instead of wasting energy (and battery margin) as heat the way a diode would.
        </p>
        <p class="obc-text">
          From there, the board splits into two <strong>independently regulated rails</strong>:
          a 5V line dedicated to actuator power, and a separate 3.3V line for the MCU, sensors,
          and radio. They're deliberately isolated from each other. Servos draw sharp, noisy
          current spikes when they move — without separation, that noise would ride straight
          into the analog sensor readings and corrupt exactly the data we need to be cleanest.
        </p>
      </section>

      <section class="obc-section">
        <h2 class="obc-heading">Sensing & State Estimation</h2>
        <p class="obc-text">
          Altitude and orientation come from two sensors working together: a <strong>BME280</strong>
          barometric sensor for altitude, and a <strong>BNO055</strong> 9-axis IMU (accelerometer,
          gyroscope, magnetometer with onboard sensor fusion) for orientation and rotational state.
        </p>
        <p class="obc-text">
          The IMU isn't soldered next to the rest of the board — it lives on its own small
          daughtercard, connected by cable, so it can be physically positioned wherever gives
          the cleanest inertial reference in the airframe, away from the electromagnetic noise
          of the board's own switching power regulators. Small decision, meaningful signal
          quality difference.
        </p>
      </section>

      <section class="obc-section">
        <h2 class="obc-heading">Guidance & Actuation</h2>
        <p class="obc-text">
          This is what turns "we built a flight computer" into "we built a flight computer
          that flies the rocket." A dedicated PWM driver (<strong>PCA9685</strong>) commands
          up to 5 servo channels: four actuate airbrakes for <strong>active drag modulation</strong>,
          letting the vehicle trim its own trajectory in real time to hit a target apogee instead
          of relying purely on motor selection and hoping — and one drives the nosecone release
          mechanism for parachute deployment.
        </p>
        <p class="obc-text">
          Splitting guidance and recovery onto dedicated, addressable channels means both
          systems can be commanded independently and verified in ground testing before they're
          ever trusted in the air.
        </p>
      </section>

      <section class="obc-section">
        <h2 class="obc-heading">Telemetry & Data Logging</h2>
        <p class="obc-text">
          Two data paths run in parallel during flight. A <strong>LoRa radio link</strong>
          streams live telemetry to the ground station, so the team can watch the flight unfold
          in real time, not just after recovery. Simultaneously, the MCU logs flight data at
          high rate to onboard microSD storage over a dedicated SDMMC interface — fast enough
          to capture the full sensor bandwidth we actually need for meaningful post-flight
          analysis.
        </p>
        <p class="obc-text">
          If the radio link drops, the flight is still fully recorded. If the rocket is never
          recovered, the team still watched it happen live. Neither data path depends on the other.
        </p>
      </section>

      <section class="obc-section">
        <h2 class="obc-heading">From Schematic to Silicon</h2>
        <p class="obc-text">
          Every part of this board — component selection, schematic capture, PCB layout, and
          design rule checks — is done in-house using <strong>KiCad</strong>. Nothing here is
          a purchased module bolted together on a breadboard; it's a purpose-built, multi-layer
          circuit board designed the same way an industry avionics team would approach it,
          scaled to what a student team can build and fly.
        </p>
      </section>

      <section class="obc-section">
        <h2 class="obc-heading">Where We Are Now</h2>
        <ul class="obc-status-list">
          <li class="obc-status-item">
            <span class="status-check">&#10003;</span>
            Power board — designed, built, and tested
          </li>
          <li class="obc-status-item">
            <span class="status-check">&#10003;</span>
            Sensor board — designed, built, and tested
          </li>
          <li class="obc-status-item">
            <span class="status-working">&#9711;</span>
            Main OBC — in active development, integrating power, sensing, guidance, and telemetry onto a single flight-ready board
          </li>
        </ul>
        <p class="obc-text obc-closing">
          What ships on Cassiopeia I is the first flight-proven version of this architecture.
          What we learn flying it becomes the starting point for Cassiopeia II.
        </p>
      </section>

      <a href="/" class="obc-back font-mono">← BACK TO DASHBOARD</a>
    </div>
  </main>
</Layout>

<style>
  .obc-page {
    display: flex;
    justify-content: center;
    padding: 2rem 0;
    min-height: calc(100vh - 4rem);
  }

  .obc-content {
    max-width: 680px;
    width: 100%;
    padding: 2.5rem;
    background: rgba(8, 12, 24, 0.85);
    border-color: rgba(139, 92, 246, 0.2);
    position: relative;
    overflow: hidden;
    display: flex;
    flex-direction: column;
    gap: 2rem;
  }

  .obc-glow-bar {
    position: absolute;
    top: 0;
    left: 0;
    right: 0;
    height: 2px;
    background: linear-gradient(to right, transparent, #8b5cf6, #06b6d4, transparent);
  }

  .obc-section-tag {
    font-size: 0.65rem;
    color: #a78bfa;
    font-weight: 600;
    letter-spacing: 0.08em;
  }

  .obc-page-title {
    font-size: 2rem;
    font-weight: 700;
    color: #ffffff;
    text-shadow: 0 0 10px rgba(139, 92, 246, 0.3);
    margin: 0;
  }

  .obc-section {
    display: flex;
    flex-direction: column;
    gap: 0.75rem;
  }

  .obc-heading {
    font-size: 1.2rem;
    font-weight: 600;
    color: #ffffff;
    margin: 0;
    padding-bottom: 0.25rem;
    border-bottom: 1px solid rgba(139, 92, 246, 0.1);
  }

  .obc-text {
    font-size: 0.88rem;
    color: var(--color-text-secondary);
    line-height: 1.7;
    margin: 0;
  }

  .obc-text strong {
    color: #ffffff;
    font-weight: 600;
  }

  .obc-text a {
    color: var(--accent-cyan);
    text-decoration: none;
  }

  .obc-status-list {
    list-style: none;
    display: flex;
    flex-direction: column;
    gap: 0.5rem;
    padding: 0;
    margin: 0;
  }

  .obc-status-item {
    display: flex;
    align-items: center;
    gap: 0.6rem;
    font-size: 0.88rem;
    color: var(--color-text-secondary);
    line-height: 1.5;
  }

  .status-check {
    color: var(--accent-emerald);
    font-weight: 700;
    font-size: 1rem;
    width: 16px;
    text-align: center;
  }

  .status-working {
    color: var(--accent-orange);
    font-size: 1rem;
    width: 16px;
    text-align: center;
  }

  .obc-closing {
    margin-top: 0.5rem;
    padding-top: 1rem;
    border-top: 1px solid rgba(139, 92, 246, 0.1);
  }

  .obc-back {
    font-size: 0.75rem;
    color: var(--color-text-muted);
    text-decoration: none;
    font-weight: 600;
    letter-spacing: 0.04em;
    transition: color 0.2s ease;
    align-self: flex-start;
  }

  .obc-back:hover {
    color: var(--accent-cyan);
  }

  .font-mono {
    font-family: 'Space Grotesk', monospace;
  }

  @media (max-width: 640px) {
    .obc-content {
      padding: 1.5rem;
    }
    .obc-page-title {
      font-size: 1.5rem;
    }
  }
</style>
